</corresp></author-notes><pub-date pub-type="ppub"><month>9</month><year>2025</year></pub-date><pub-date pub-type="epub"><day>24</day><month>7</month><year>2025</year></pub-date><volume>17</volume><issue>Suppl 3</issue><issue-id pub-id-type="pmc-issue-id">499593</issue-id><fpage>S2557</fpage><lpage>S2559</lpage><history><date date-type="received"><day>04</day><month>5</month><year>2025</year></date><date date-type="rev-recd"><day>05</day><month>6</month><year>2025</year></date><date date-type="accepted"><day>06</day><month>6</month><year>2025</year></date></history><pub-history><event event-type="pmc-release"><date><day>01</day><month>09</month><year>2025</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-live"><date><day>29</day><month>10</month><year>2025</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-last-change"><date iso-8601-date="2025-10-30 09:25:35.933"><day>30</day><month>10</month><year>2025</year></date></event></pub-history><permissions><copyright-statement>Copyright: © 2025 Journal of Pharmacy and Bioallied Sciences</copyright-statement><copyright-year>2025</copyright-year><license><ali:license_ref xmlns:ali="http://www.niso.org/schemas/ali/1.0/" specific-use="textmining" content-type="ccbyncsalicense">https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/</ali:license_ref><license-p>This is an open access journal, and articles are distributed under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 License, which allows others to remix, tweak, and build upon the work non-commercially, as long as appropriate credit is given and the new creations are licensed under the identical terms.</license-p></license></permissions><self-uri xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" content-type="pmc-pdf" xlink:href="JPBS-17-2557.pdf"/><abstract><title>A<sc>BSTRACT</sc></title><sec><title>Background:</title><p>Long COVID refers to persistent symptoms lasting weeks or months after recovery from acute COVID-19. These symptoms can affect multiple systems and impair quality of life.</p></sec><sec><title>Objective:</title><p>To assess the prevalence, pattern, and probable pathophysiological mechanisms of long COVID symptoms in recovered patients.</p></sec><sec><title>Materials and Methods:</title><p>A cross-sectional study was conducted over 12 months among 210 adults recovered from COVID-19 (≥12 weeks postinfection). Clinical evaluation, lab investigations, and imaging were used to identify post-COVID symptoms and explore underlying mechanisms.</p></sec><sec><title>Results:</title><p>Common symptoms included fatigue (67.6%), breathlessness (42.8%), cognitive issues (39.5%), and myalgia (34.7%). Neuropsychiatric complaints were noted in 41%, while 29% had cardiopulmonary sequelae. Elevated inflammatory markers correlated with symptom persistence (<italic toggle="yes">P</italic> &lt; 0.05).</p></sec><sec><title>Conclusion:</title><p>Long COVID involves diverse symptoms, primarily fatigue and neurorespiratory complaints. Immune dysregulation and systemic inflammation appear central to its pathophysiology.</p></sec></abstract><kwd-group><title>K<sc>EYWORDS</sc>:</title><kwd><italic toggle="yes">Breathlessness</italic></kwd><kwd><italic toggle="yes">fatigue</italic></kwd><kwd><italic toggle="yes">inflammation</italic></kwd><kwd><italic toggle="yes">long COVID</italic></kwd><kwd><italic toggle="yes">post-viral syndrome</italic></kwd></kwd-group><funding-group><funding-statement>
Nil.
</funding-statement></funding-group><custom-meta-group><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-qastatus</meta-name><meta-value>0</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-live</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-embargo</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-released</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-open-access</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-olf</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-manuscript</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-legally-suppressed</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-has-pdf</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-has-supplement</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-pdf-only</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-suppress-copyright</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-is-real-version</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-is-scanned-article</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-preprint</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-in-epmc</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-license-ref</meta-name><meta-value>CC BY-NC-SA</meta-value></custom-meta></custom-meta-group></article-meta></front><body><sec sec-type="intro"><title>I<sc>NTRODUCTION</sc></title><p>COVID-19, caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), has resulted in widespread morbidity and mortality globally.[<xref rid="R1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>] While the acute phase has been extensively studied, increasing attention is now focused on “Long COVID”, a condition characterized by persistent, unexplained symptoms lasting beyond 12 weeks postinfection.[<xref rid="R2" ref-type="bibr">2</xref>] These symptoms, including fatigue, dyspnea, cognitive disturbances, and psychiatric complaints, affect individuals regardless of age or initial disease severity.[<xref rid="R3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref>] Proposed mechanisms include immune dysregulation, chronic inflammation, and autonomic dysfunction.[<xref rid="R4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>] Although global studies have described varying patterns of long COVID, region-specific data from India—particularly integrating symptom profiles with laboratory and radiological findings—remain scarce. This study aimed to evaluate the clinical and biological spectra of long COVID in Indian patients to inform targeted management strategies.[<xref rid="R5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>]</p></sec><sec sec-type="materials|methods"><title>M<sc>ATERIALS AND</sc> M<sc>ETHODS</sc></title><p>A cross-sectional observational study was conducted over 12 months among adults (≥18 years) with confirmed COVID-19 infection (via RT-PCR or RAT), recovered for at least 12 weeks. Patients with chronic illnesses or psychiatric conditions that could confound assessment were excluded. Using purposive sampling, 210 participants were enrolled from outpatient follow-up and telephonic screening. Data were collected via structured interviews using a pretested questionnaire covering persistent respiratory, neurological, musculoskeletal, and psychiatric symptoms. Clinical evaluation, routine labs, inflammatory markers (CRP, IL-6), and chest imaging (X-ray or HRCT) were used to assess residual organ involvement. Statistical analysis included descriptive and inferential tests, with significance set at <italic toggle="yes">P</italic> &lt; 0.05. Ethical approval and informed consent were obtained.</p></sec><sec sec-type="results"><title>R<sc>ESULTS</sc></title><p>The study analyzed 210 patients who had recovered from COVID-19 infection at least 12 weeks prior. The mean age of participants was 41.2 ± 12.7 years, with a slight male predominance (53.8%). A wide array of persistent symptoms was noted, most commonly fatigue, breathlessness, cognitive difficulties, and musculoskeletal complaints. The following tables summarize the associations between long COVID symptoms and selected demographic, clinical, and laboratory parameters.</p><p><xref rid="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t001" ref-type="table">Table 1</xref> highlights the demographic profile and distribution of long COVID symptoms. Fatigue was significantly more prevalent in participants aged &gt;40 years.</p><table-wrap position="float" id="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t001" orientation="portrait"><label>Table 1</label><caption><p>Association of long COVID symptoms with demographic variables</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Variable</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fatigue (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=142)</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">No fatigue (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=68)</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<italic toggle="yes">P</italic>
</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Age ≤40/&gt;40 years</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">61/81</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">41/27</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.019</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Gender (M/F)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">76/66</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">37/31</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.918</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Urban/Rural</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">84/58</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">39/29</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.895</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Vaccinated (yes/no)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">101/41</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">53/15</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.276</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap><p><xref rid="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t002" ref-type="table">Table 2</xref> summarizes the overall frequency of long COVID symptoms reported by the study population. Fatigue and breathlessness were the most prevalent symptoms.</p><table-wrap position="float" id="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t002" orientation="portrait"><label>Table 2</label><caption><p>Prevalence of long COVID symptoms among participants (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=210)</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Symptom</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><italic toggle="yes">n</italic> (%)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fatigue</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">142 (67.6)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Breathlessness</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">90 (42.8)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Cognitive difficulties</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">83 (39.5)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Myalgia</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">73 (34.7)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Sleep disturbances</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">68 (32.3)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Anxiety or depression</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">64 (30.4)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Loss of taste/smell</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">51 (24.2)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Chest pain/palpitations</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">48 (22.8)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Headache</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">46 (21.9)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Cough</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">40 (19.0)</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap><p><xref rid="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t003" ref-type="table">Table 3</xref> shows patients with moderate-to-severe initial COVID-19 illness had significantly higher chances of reporting persistent symptoms, particularly respiratory and neurological ones.</p><table-wrap position="float" id="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t003" orientation="portrait"><label>Table 3</label><caption><p>Long COVID symptoms based on severity of initial COVID-19 illness</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Symptom</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Mild (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=102)</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Mod-severe (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=108)</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<italic toggle="yes">P</italic>
</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fatigue</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">58 (56.9%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">84 (77.8%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.001</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Breathlessness</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">31 (30.4%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">59 (54.6%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.002</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Cognitive issues</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">33 (32.3%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">50 (46.3%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.042</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Anxiety/depression</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">25 (24.5%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">39 (36.1%)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.071</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap><p><xref rid="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t004" ref-type="table">Table 4</xref> demonstrates the laboratory findings in patients with and without persistent symptoms. Elevated CRP and IL-6 levels were significantly associated with long COVID.</p><table-wrap position="float" id="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t004" orientation="portrait"><label>Table 4</label><caption><p>Comparison of inflammatory markers in symptomatic vs asymptomatic participants</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Marker</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Symptomatic (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=161)</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Asymptomatic (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=49)</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<italic toggle="yes">P</italic>
</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">CRP (mg/L), mean±SD</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">8.1±3.5</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">4.3±2.1</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&lt;0.001</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">IL-6 (pg/mL), mean</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">19.6±8.3</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">11.2±6.7</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&lt;0.001</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">D-dimer (ng/mL)</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">412±88</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">361±72</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">0.031</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap><p><xref rid="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t005" ref-type="table">Table 5</xref> outlines the radiological findings among patients with persistent respiratory symptoms. Fibrotic changes and ground-glass opacities were the most common abnormalities on chest imaging.</p><table-wrap position="float" id="jpbs.jpbs_880_25-t005" orientation="portrait"><label>Table 5</label><caption><p>Radiological abnormalities in participants with respiratory complaints (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic>=90)</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Imaging finding</th><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><italic toggle="yes">n</italic> (%)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fibrotic changes</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">26 (28.9)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Ground-glass opacities</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">19 (21.1)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Persistent infiltrates</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">11 (12.2)</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Normal imaging</td><td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">34 (37.8)</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap></sec><sec sec-type="discussion"><title>D<sc>ISCUSSION</sc></title><p>This study highlights the significant burden of long COVID symptoms in patients who have recovered from SARS-CoV-2 infection, with fatigue, breathlessness, and cognitive dysfunction being the most frequently reported complaints.[<xref rid="R6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>] Older age and moderate-to-severe acute illness were associated with a higher prevalence of persistent symptoms. The findings are consistent with international data, emphasizing the global nature of post-COVID complications. Elevated inflammatory markers, particularly CRP and IL-6, suggest that ongoing systemic inflammation plays a central role in the pathophysiology of long COVID.[<xref rid="R7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref>] Neuropsychiatric symptoms, including anxiety and brain fog, further indicate the virus’s impact on the central nervous system and possibly the autonomic system. Radiological abnormalities in a subset of patients support the hypothesis of chronic pulmonary involvement even months after clinical recovery.[<xref rid="R8" ref-type="bibr">8</xref>] These observations underscore the need for multidisciplinary follow-up and tailored rehabilitation strategies in post-COVID care.</p></sec><sec sec-type="conclusion"><title>C<sc>ONCLUSION</sc></title><p>Long COVID presents with a broad spectrum of persistent symptoms that affect physical, respiratory, and neuropsychiatric health even months after recovery. Early recognition and targeted multidisciplinary management are essential to reduce long-term morbidity and improve patient outcomes.</p><sec sec-type="COI-statement"><title>Conflict of interest</title><p>Nil.</p></sec></sec></body><back><ref-list><title>R<sc>EFERENCES</sc></title><ref id="R1"><label>1</label><element-citation publication-type="journal" publication-format="print"><person-group person-group-type="author">
